Publishing ports.

A container's processes bind to ports inside their own network namespace, and by default those ports are not reachable from outside the host, because the bridge is private. To let outside traffic in, you have to publish a port, and the publish flag is how you do it.

The basic form takes a host port and a container port, and it reads as, take whatever arrives on this host port and forward it to that container port. So publishing host port eighty-eighty to container port eighty makes a request to the host's port eighty-eighty reach the web server inside the container. There are a few important variations. By default the publish binds on all host interfaces, but you can prefix a specific address, and binding only to local-host is much safer for any development service that does not need to be reachable from the wider network. You can also pick the protocol explicitly when you need u-d-p instead of t-c-p. And if you give only the container port and omit the host port, docker binds to a random free host port, which you read back from the port command or the container listing.

There is also a capital-P form that auto-publishes every port the image's expose instruction declared, each to a random host port, which is convenient for quick testing but almost never what production wants. And it is worth recalling from notebook two that expose itself is just documentation. It does not publish anything. It only hints that the image listens on a given port, which the capital-P form reads to know what to map. You can always publish a port that was never exposed. Expose is a hint, not a gate.
